# Memoization (Components) üß†

By default, if a Parent re-renders, all Children re-render.

Use `React.memo` to skip re-rendering a component if its props haven't changed.

```jsx
const MyComponent = React.memo(function MyComponent(props) {
  /* only renders if props change */
});
```

# useMemo Hook üóÑÔ∏è

Memoize **expensive calculations**.

```jsx
const sortedList = useMemo(() => {
  return sortHugeArray(list);
}, [list]);
```
This ensures `sortHugeArray` only runs when `list` changes, not on every render.

# useCallback Hook üìû

Memoize **functions**.

If you pass a function as a prop to a `React.memo` component, it will still re-render because a new function is created on every render.

`useCallback` caches the function instance.

```jsx
const handleClick = useCallback(() => {
  doSomething(a, b);
}, [a, b]);
```

# Memo Example üíª

<!-- FULL_CODE_START
import React, { useState, useMemo } from 'react';

function App() {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);
  const [text, setText] = useState('');

  // Expensive calculation
  const expensiveValue = useMemo(() => {
    console.log('Calculating...');
    let total = 0;
    for (let i = 0; i < 1000000; i++) {
      total += i;
    }
    return total;
  }, []); // Empty array = run once

  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Computed: {expensiveValue}</h2>
      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>Count: {count}</button>
      <input value={text} onChange={e => setText(e.target.value)} />
    </div>
  );
}
FULL_CODE_END -->
